#max_cycle stores the total number of cycles for each engine
grouped_by_engine = train.groupby(by="engine_no")
max_cycle = grouped_by_engine["cycle_no"].max()
    
train = train.merge(max_cycle.to_frame(name='max_cycle'), left_on='engine_no', right_index=True)
    
# Calculate remaining useful life for each row
RUL = train["max_cycle"] - train["cycle_no"]
train["RUL"] = RUL
    
#drop max_cycle column since we have got the needed RUL column now
train = train.drop("max_cycle", axis=1)

#A function to return the performance of our ML models
def evaluate(y_true, y_pred, label='test'):
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
    variance = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print('{} set RMSE:{}, R2:{}'.format(label, rmse, variance))

#We redefine RUL as constant upto a point and then decline linearly, from our graphs, sensor readings stay constant till 120-150
k=120
for i in range(20):
    y_train_clipped = y_train.clip(upper=k)
    svr = SVR(kernel='linear')
    svr.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train_clipped)

# predict and evaluate
    print("Value of k: ",k)
    y_pred_train = svr.predict(X_train_scaled)
    evaluate(y_train_clipped, y_pred_train, 'train')

    y_pred_test = svr.predict(X_test_scaled)
    evaluate(y_test, y_pred_test)
    
    k=k+1
